  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "Cognitive scientists have known about these information-processing bottlenecks for a long time, but they are not obvious from ordinary reflection, and they often have to be demonstrated to be accepted by naïve experimental participants and members of the non-expert public.",
    "It's likely that one reason for this is that the offloading strategies people routinely adopt allow them to compensate for these deficits and fluently respond to their surroundings in a way that would not be predictable from an examination of their purely internal information-processing capacities.",
    "Consequently, it's been suggested that much of what we pretheoretically take to be ordinary cognition would be unavailable without offloading (Donald 1993; Wilson, 2004; Clark, 2008; Risko & Gilbert, 2016).",
    "What are we to make of this?",
    "For defenders of HEC, the pervasive and transformative role of offloading in our everyday cognitive agency amounts to evidence that the bodily and environmental objects, structures and events that we offload cognition onto -call these 'external resources' -should be counted as constitutive parts of the cognitive processes they help realise."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "Consequently, it's been suggested that much of what we pretheoretically take to be ordinary cognition would be unavailable without offloading (Donald 1993; Wilson, 2004; Clark, 2008; Risko & Gilbert, 2016)."
  ]
